Since I'm using **NetworkManager** on Arch, Instead, manually adding ip addr you should use `nmcli` (command line) to make these settings permanent.

Here is how to set up your specific IP schema (`192.168.1.105`) and ensure your laptop acts as the "Internet Provider" for my Proxmox server.

### 1. Configure the Static IP on Arch
Assuming your ethernet interface is named `enp2s0` (check with `ip link`), run these commands:

Bash

```
# Create a profile named 'Lab-Link' with your static IP
sudo nmcli con add type ethernet con-name Lab-Link ifname enp2s0 ip4 192.168.1.105/24 gw4 192.168.1.1

# Set the DNS
sudo nmcli con mod Lab-Link ipv4.dns "192.168.1.150 and secondary dns 1.1.1.1"

# Set the method to manual (static)
sudo nmcli con mod Lab-Link ipv4.method manual

# Bring the connection up
sudo nmcli con up Lab-Link

### 2. Share Wi-Fi Internet to Ethernet

To allow your Proxmox PC (at `192.168.1.101`) to get internet through your laptop's Wi-Fi, you can use the built-in "Shared" mode in NetworkManager.
This automatically handles the NAT and IP forwarding for you.

**To do this via the interface (Easiest):**

1. Run `nmtui`.
    
2. Go to **Edit a connection**.
    
3. Select your Ethernet profile.
    
4. Set **IPv4 CONFIGURATION** to `<Shared>`.
    

